name: Seats, Outside Classic Diner, 2008
description:
From the series 'Going to the Dogs', for which Katherine spent 3 months documenting the closure of Walthamstow Greyhound Stadium. Walthamstow Stadium was the best known and loved of all the UK greyhound tracks, it employed over 500 people and it's sorely missed. It was bought by a housing association and closed in 2008 and is currently standing disused and empty. 

These empty red seats were outside the 'Classic Diner' on the 'Popular' side of the track. 

This is a Archival inkjet print in an edition of 15. Each print is signed and dated on the back, and will be packed carefully in a cardboard tube. 

There are two sizes available, either 18 x 12" or 12 x 8"

name: Interior, Popular Side, 2008
description:
From the series 'Going to the Dogs', for which Katherine spent 3 months documenting the closure of Walthamstow Greyhound Stadium. Walthamstow Stadium was the best known and loved of all the UK greyhound tracks, it employed over 500 people and it's sorely missed. It was bought by a housing association and closed in 2008 and is currently standing disused and empty. 

This interior is from the 'Popular side'. The stadium was divided into two sides, the 'Popular side' being the cheaper of the two. The fixtures and fittings, and food available were all of a cheaper quality but that's not to say it didn't lack atmosphere. In many ways it had much more character that the main side. Here one of the illuminated signs is shown next to a tote booth. All of these signs were ripped out by souvenir hunters on the last night. 

This is a Archival inkjet print in an edition of 15. Each print is signed and dated on the back, and will be packed carefully in a cardboard tube. 

There are two sizes available, either 18 x 12" or 12 x 8"

name: Walthamstow Stadium facade
description:
From the series 'Going to the Dogs', for which Katherine spent 3 months documenting the closure of Walthamstow Greyhound Stadium. Walthamstow Stadium was the best known and loved of all the UK greyhound tracks, it employed over 500 people and it's sorely missed. It was bought by a housing association and closed in 2008 and is currently standing disused and empty. 

The famous 'Walthamstow Stadium' sign seen in the daytime. The listed frontage can be seen for miles around and has been a local landmark since 1933. It is hoped this will be preserved even when L&Q build tower blocks behind it. 

This is a Archival inkjet print in an edition of 30. Each print is signed and dated on the back, and will be packed carefully in a cardboard tube. 

There are two sizes available, either 18 x 12" or 12 x 8" or 30 x 20"

name: Stadium Facade at Night, 2008
description:
From the series 'Going to the Dogs', for which Katherine spent 3 months documenting the closure of Walthamstow Greyhound Stadium. Walthamstow Stadium was the best known and loved of all the UK greyhound tracks, it employed over 500 people and it's sorely missed. It was bought by a housing association and closed in 2008 and is currently standing disused and empty. 

It was at night that the stadium came alive, and this photograph shows the famous Art Deco listed frontage neon. The sign could be seen from miles and was an exciting and familiar local landmark until the stadium closed, and since then the lights have remained off. 

This is a Archival inkjet print in an edition of 30. Each print is signed and dated on the back, and will be packed carefully in a cardboard tube. 

There are two sizes available, either 18 x 12" or 12 x 8" or 30 x 20"
